Ever since the Agile manifesto was published in 2001, the battle between an agile approach to application development and maintenance has been waged. In my opinion, the battle is over. The solution is an agile waterfall. While my day job is in IT, I have the privilege of performing with a rock choir called Revv52. In January we performed our January show called Epic 80's - Don't Stop Believing. This show is a classic example of the Agile Waterfall.

# Waterfall Phase

In order to get a production on stage, there needs to be a minimum viable product before we can release the show to our audience. There are set stages that the production goes through to get to the stage and we have a fixed timeframe for when the show will be performed. These stages area aligned to most project methodologies as follows:

- **Concept (Idea)** - Every performance we do starts at the concept stage. The idea for Epic 80s started before the pandemic with our artistic director asking each of the Revv52 cast members their favorite 80s songs. This yielded over 100 songs where we only have around 20. For application development these ideas come from user demand, regulatory requirements, competition. Most larger organizations use some form of governance to select the best ideas to move forward into the next stage.
- **Scoring (Design)** - For this show, while members were enjoying the Canadian summer, our artistic director had decided that we would produce an 80s show in chronological order. That meant selecting songs that created an arc over two acts that kept our audiences engaged. Through the summer and into the fall, the Revv52 arrangers took the selected songs and arranged them for a 52 member choral ensemble in up to 8 voice ranges. This is equivalent to having a design increment where the specifications are being developed based on the 'features' that have been selected for this 'Epic'
- **Learning the Music (Development)** - Now the hard part for the members. Learning and memorizing the music starts with a series of sight reading rehearsals. This can lead to revisions to the music and sometimes replacing songs entirely. More complex songs are given more time to develop our skills and add the nuances that will bring the songs to life. Sometimes we even perform songs as a proof of concept to test how an audience might respond at a special performance.

From an application development perspective this is akin to developing the various components of an application in an object-oriented way since each song is a discrete component of the show. It is time consuming, but a essential part of the show, but for the most part more like developing the business logic and data layers of the application.

- **Costumes and Choreography (Visual User Experience)** - As we get closer to the show it's time to think about the visual aspects of the show. A wardrobe style guide is provided to the cast and for some we were able to dig through our closets, for most there were some additions to develop get back to the 80s. We also add choreography for within a particular sone, but also how we transition from one song to the next.
- For developers, this is somewhat akin to adding the user experience layer and determining the individual screens for each object as well has the application dynamics that take us from one screen to another.
- **Adding the Band (Integration Testing)** - Up until this point we have been using a rehearsal accompanist to helps us learn the music. They are essential as they (largely) play the notes the members are singing vs. what the actual accompaniment will be. Adding a lead and base guitar, one or two keyboards and a drummer changes many of the cues for the singers. This is somewhat like taking the code and putting it in the test environment to see how it performs.

  

